Hardwell brings on the burgeoning talent, MAKJ, to foster an explosive new sound that has been tested and proven throughout this year. As the teaser video runs through scenes of Los Angeles and the Palladium show, "Countdown" takes shape with a soft melody line that opens up to a lush chorus of synth strings on top of drums. A brief pause passes and the countdown ensues, raising anticipation for the drop and creating a strong sense of euphoria. Then the hard kicks and horn-like synth burst through with brute force taking the energy level to new heights. Following the main segment, it reaches a super charged climax as the second drop moves in with an added synth for full effect. The fact that "Countdown" has been one of the most buzzed about tracks for months is a testament to Hardwell's signature, festival anthem sound has been manifested at its fundamental core time and time again.

There’s a little bit of a story behind this remix.  Outkast was one of our favorite groups growing up, and Roses was always our favorite song of theirs.  It was the song that got played on the bus in 6th grade, the one on our high school basketball warmup CD, and the one we put on at every party in college.  We had been writing remix ideas for Roses for upwards of four years, and a few months ago we decided to sit down and actually finish it.  This song has been particularly special to us for a long time and it was a blast reimagining it in a way that speaks to our own musical tastes.  Hope you all love it as much as we do!

meta.title: Blastaa
meta.description:
Full Mad Liberation Album Download Available at:
http://www.mynameisgriz.com

Mad Liberation is a collection of songs that I have been working on for the past year that ranged from mostly original compositions to varied sample work (retro vinyl recordings and new all original recordings); digital synthesis that took me weeks to master; to live instrumentation tediously and soulfully recorded by myself and some of my very good friends. 

This collection of noise - to me - became an album, a sound in a whole, an idea free from limits of thought and more an idea of the heart and soul. Mad Liberation is a piece of me that is representative of my past, breathes life into my present, and is a taste of the future. 

I don't have fancy recording equipment, amazing speakers, crazy keyboards, complicated sample packs, proper studio time, cutting edge midi controllers, or outboard mixing gear. 

What I do have is an endless imagination of the future/now, unrelenting will, constant fascination, and a heart that has no capacity to stop loving and trying. 

This business - when you boil it down - is not about the machine, but about the man. Even electronic music is humanistic. We breath life into these dead things to make them whisper and ROAR!! I am inspired by that fact, and this is what sets me free.

This is Mad Liberation

 GRiZ

P.S. Thank you all for continuing to support my sound. I am so blown away, impressed, and excited at how many of you guys come out and show love at my shows! Thanks for being such a big part of it!! (this is only the beginning for #teamGRiZ)

meta.description:
GURU021 - Sartek - 'Back To The Future' is out on 8th May.

• Subscribe to GURU on YouTube: bit.ly/GURU-YTsub
• Subscribe to GURU on Spotify here: bit.ly/GURU-spotify

Fast rising Indian producer Sartek is at it once again, dropping another huge club bomb for Gregori Klosman’s Guru. The imprint has been a staunch admirer of the New Delhi native during the early stages of his career and it’s already not hard to see why. Every time this man gets behind the mixing desk the fires are fuelled and a jet-­pack explosion of modern house music powers through the speakers. Like his last effort on Guru, “Dopamine” Sartek finds the perfect balance between the intense and the melodic with “Back to the Future.” After floating, jangling piano keys and emotive synths initiate the track in almost laidback surroundings, all of a sudden ferocious basslines and kicking drums jolt in and attack the central nervous system. But before it hammers you into submission, the track breaks down and then opens up into airy melodies and what turns out to be, a false sense of calm. Before you know it, the throttle is pulled and we are right back into full swing. Devastating stuff!
